# Report on Promoting Interprofessional Collaboration During Patient Transitions

## Introduction

Patient transitions—defined as the movement of patients between healthcare settings or providers—are critical junctures in healthcare delivery that significantly impact patient safety, quality of care, and health outcomes. Effective interprofessional collaboration during these transitions is essential to ensure continuity of care, reduce medical errors, and improve patient satisfaction. This report provides a comprehensive analysis of how healthcare facilities can promote interprofessional collaboration during patient transitions, drawing on evidence-based practices, leadership strategies, communication frameworks, and technological tools. The report synthesizes current best practices and frameworks, with a focus on actionable strategies and resources that facilities can implement.

---

## The Importance of Interprofessional Collaboration in Patient Transitions

Interprofessional collaboration involves multiple health professionals from different disciplines working together to deliver comprehensive care. During patient transitions, collaboration is crucial because:

- It reduces communication breakdowns that can lead to medical errors and adverse events.
- It ensures that all relevant patient information is accurately shared and understood.
- It supports coordinated care planning and shared decision-making.
- It enhances patient and family engagement in care processes.
- It improves overall patient safety and satisfaction.

Studies have shown that poor communication and siloed approaches during transitions contribute to increased readmissions, emergency visits, and patient dissatisfaction ([Patel & Landrigan, 2019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pcl.2019.03.004)).

---

## Foundational Elements Supporting Interprofessional Collaboration

The Joint Commission identifies seven foundational elements for safe and effective patient care transitions that underpin interprofessional collaboration ([Wolters Kluwer Health, 2019](https://www.wolterskluwer.com/en/solutions/ovid/best-practices-for-safe-and-successful-care-transitions)):

| Foundation Element             | Description                                                                                  |
|-------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Early Identification of Risk   | Recognizing patients at high risk for adverse events during transitions.                      |
| Leadership Support             | Engaging organizational leaders to prioritize and support transition processes.              |
| Medication Management          | Ensuring accurate medication reconciliation and management across settings.                   |
| Multidisciplinary Collaboration | Facilitating teamwork among diverse healthcare professionals.                                 |
| Patient and Family Engagement  | Involving patients and families as active partners in care planning and transitions.          |
| Transfer of Information        | Using standardized communication tools to share patient data accurately and timely.          |
| Transitional Planning          | Coordinating care plans that anticipate patient needs post-transition.                        |

Implementing these foundations promotes a culture of collaboration and shared responsibility among healthcare teams.

